35519.object_definition_value: Succession disputes between the sons of Kodros in Athens result in some of them leading a large scale migration across the Aegean, perhaps stopping at Naxos on the way, and founding new cities in Anatolia. The leader of this migration is sometimes said to be Neileus, the founder claimed by Miletos, and sometimes said to be Androklos, the founder claimed by Ephesos. The composition of the accompanying large group is described variously by the different sources.

35519.object_definition_value: Having been sent as an offering to Delphi by the Epigonoi, Manto is instructed to go to Kolophon or Klaros, depending on the version. Teiresias may or may not travel with her, depending on if he has already died in the version. Manto founds both the city and the sanctuary, names them, and gives birth to her son Mopsos there, who is either said to be the son of Apollo or of Rhakios/Lakios (who in some versions Manto meets in Anatolia and marries). Manto and Mopsos are here at the end of the Trojan War, when Calchas and his companions visit and challenge Mopsos to a competition of prophetic skill.

35519.object_definition_value: After quarrelling with Agamemnon in the ruins of Troy, Menelaos avoids the storm that wrecks so many other nostoi by sailing south via Egypt. In some versions of the story, the true Helen had been here all along, while the one at Troy was an eidolon.

object_definition_value: Band of companions of a hero

35519.object_definition_value: Agamemnon sets out from Troy by sea, but puts in at Tenedos to avoid a storm (the same storm foretold by Calchas and which kills many of the returning Achaeans on their way home from Troy). Afterwards, he sails home to Mykenae and to Clytemnestra.
